"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1127305","Department for Education","false","2019-05-23","<p>The information requested, regarding the proportion of funding which comes from donations by parents or guardians of pupils, is not held centrally. Schools’ financial returns show that overall income from donations and voluntary funds has remained steady at about 0.7% of schools’ overall budgets since 2011-12.</p><p> </p>","Bognor Regis and Littlehampton","Nick Gibb",,"2019-05-23T13:52:15.273Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1127305/answer","Biography information for Nick Gibb","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1127305/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1127305/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2019-05-17","Schools: Charitable Donations","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, what recent estimate he has made of the proportion of comprehensive primary school funding which comes from donations by parents or guardians of pupils.","false","Biography information for Chuka Umunna","Streatham","Chuka Umunna","255676"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1127306","Treasury","false","2019-05-21","<p>The FCA is an independent body responsible for regulating and supervising the financial services industry. It sets the conduct standards required of insurance firms in relation to their business.</p><p> </p><p>The FCA’s rules require insurers to handle claims fairly and promptly; provide reasonable guidance to help a policyholder make a claim, and appropriate information on its progress; not reject a claim unreasonably; and settle claims promptly once settlement terms are agreed. It is important that insurers treat customers fairly and the Government supports the FCA in carrying out its responsibilities.</p>","Salisbury","John Glen","255669 ; 255670","2019-05-21T14:42:59.817Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1127306/answer","Biography information for John Glen","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1127306/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1127306/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","Treasury","2019-05-17","Insurance Companies","1","House of Commons","To ask the Chancellor of the Exchequer, what steps he has taken to make sure that adequate interim payments to third parties are made promptly by insurance companies after those companies have accepted liability.","false","Biography information for Joseph  Johnson","Orpington","Joseph Johnson","255668"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1127307","Treasury","false","2019-05-21","<p>The FCA is an independent body responsible for regulating and supervising the financial services industry. It sets the conduct standards required of insurance firms in relation to their business.</p><p> </p><p>The FCA’s rules require insurers to handle claims fairly and promptly; provide reasonable guidance to help a policyholder make a claim, and appropriate information on its progress; not reject a claim unreasonably; and settle claims promptly once settlement terms are agreed. It is important that insurers treat customers fairly and the Government supports the FCA in carrying out its responsibilities.</p>","Salisbury","John Glen","255668 ; 255670","2019-05-21T14:42:59.87Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1127307/answer","Biography information for John Glen","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1127307/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1127307/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","Treasury","2019-05-17","Insurance Companies","1","House of Commons","To ask the Chancellor of the Exchequer, what steps he is taking to stop insurance companies delaying interim payments to third parties to take advantage of potential changes to the Ogden discount rate.","false","Biography information for Joseph  Johnson","Orpington","Joseph Johnson","255669"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1127308","Treasury","false","2019-05-21","<p>The FCA is an independent body responsible for regulating and supervising the financial services industry. It sets the conduct standards required of insurance firms in relation to their business.</p><p> </p><p>The FCA’s rules require insurers to handle claims fairly and promptly; provide reasonable guidance to help a policyholder make a claim, and appropriate information on its progress; not reject a claim unreasonably; and settle claims promptly once settlement terms are agreed. It is important that insurers treat customers fairly and the Government supports the FCA in carrying out its responsibilities.</p>","Salisbury","John Glen","255668 ; 255669","2019-05-21T14:42:59.907Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1127308/answer","Biography information for John Glen","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1127308/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1127308/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","Treasury","2019-05-17","Insurance Companies","1","House of Commons","To ask the Chancellor of the Exchequer, if he will make it his policy to introduce a legally binding code of conduct for insurance companies to protect (a) defendants and (b) claimants from the start of a third party claim to the final settlement.","false","Biography information for Joseph  Johnson","Orpington","Joseph Johnson","255670"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1127309","Ministry of Justice","false","2019-05-28","<p>The vast majority of claims against insurers in the civil justice system settle before court proceedings stage, as reflected in the statistics published by the Compensation Recovery Unit.</p><p> </p><p>Settlements are a matter for the parties to an individual dispute to reach agreement on, but the Government seeks to promote pre-court settlement – for example by the development of pre-action protocols.</p><p> </p><p>In terms of road traffic accident related personal injury claims under £5,000, the Government is introducing a new IT Platform, in April 2020, which will enable such claimants to communicate effectively with the at-fault insurer to efficiently progress and settle their claim during the pre-action stage without the need for court proceedings.</p>","Blackpool North and Cleveleys","Paul Maynard",,"2019-05-28T16:14:52.87Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1127309/answer","Biography information for Paul Maynard","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1127309/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1127309/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2019-05-17","Insurance Companies: Civil Proceedings","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, what steps he is taking to ensure that greater numbers of insurance cases are resolved before they reach court proceedings.","false","Biography information for Joseph  Johnson","Orpington","Joseph Johnson","255671"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1127310","Ministry of Justice","false","2019-05-28","<p>The Government has no plans to bring forward such proposals.</p><p>It is for parties to personal injury claims to resolve their differences in the first instance, making use of pre-action protocols which put in place procedures designed to encourage earlier resolution of disputes.</p><p> </p><p>Currently there is a portal for lower value road traffic accident (RTA), public liability and employer liability claims which assists in achieving settlement of disputes. In addition, the Government is introducing a new IT Platform, in April 2020, which will enable RTA claimants to communicate effectively with the at-fault insurer to progress and settle their claim during the pre-action stage.</p><p> </p><p>Where disputes cannot be resolved by these means, the claimant has the option to pursue court proceedings.</p>","Blackpool North and Cleveleys","Paul Maynard",,"2019-05-28T16:19:27.19Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1127310/answer","Biography information for Paul Maynard","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1127310/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1127310/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2019-05-17","Personal Injury: Compensation","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, if he will bring forward legislative proposals to establish an ombudsman with legal powers to enforce decisions on third party personal injury claims before court proceedings are initiated.","false","Biography information for Joseph  Johnson","Orpington","Joseph Johnson","255672"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1127311","Department for Digital, Culture, Media and Sport","false","2019-05-22","<p>We recognise the potential for change that DNS over HTTPS introduces and are working with industry to ensure that regulatory needs can be provided for and to seek solutions to any potential issues with online protections.</p>","Stourbridge","Margot James",,"2019-05-22T11:00:24.513Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1127311/answer","Biography information for Margot James","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1127311/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1127311/answer",,,,,"10","Digital, Culture, Media and Sport","Digital, Culture, Media and Sport","2019-05-17","Internet: Safety","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Digital, Culture, Media and Sport, what assessment he has made of the potential effect on the protections for children and young people proposed in the Online Harms White Paper of adopting DNS over HTTPS.","false","Biography information for Tom Watson","West Bromwich East","Tom Watson","255664"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1127312","Department for Digital, Culture, Media and Sport","false","2019-05-22","<p>We are aware that the adoption of DNS over HTTPS could impact online parental controls. We are working with industry with industry to understand both their plans for the implementation of DNS over HTTPS, and for solutions to maintain online parental controls.</p>","Stourbridge","Margot James",,"2019-05-22T11:01:37.377Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1127312/answer","Biography information for Margot James","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1127312/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1127312/answer",,,,,"10","Digital, Culture, Media and Sport","Digital, Culture, Media and Sport","2019-05-17","Internet: Safety","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Digital, Culture, Media and Sport, what estimate he has made of the number of people whose online parental controls could be affected by the adoption of DNS over HTTPS.","false","Biography information for Tom Watson","West Bromwich East","Tom Watson","255665"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1127313","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2019-05-28","<p>We are deeply concerned by reports of an alleged airstrike on a petrol station at a hospital facility on 26 March 2019. Our officials have been in contact with Save the Children, who fund the hospital, about this alleged incident and have raised this matter with the Saudi-led Coalition, who have announced an investigation.</p><p>We are also deeply concerned at reports of an explosion at a warehouse near two schools in Sa’wan on 7 April 2019. We have raised the incident with the Coalition who have announced an investigation in line with standard practices. We endorse the statement of the Special Envoy of the UN Secretary General of 9 April and continue to call on all parties to the conflict in Yemen to exercise restraint, comply fully with international humanitarian law and implement the Stockholm Agreement without delay in order to improve the humanitarian situation in Yemen.</p>","South West Wiltshire","Dr Andrew Murrison",,"2019-05-28T10:47:28.423Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1127313/answer","Biography information for Dr Andrew Murrison","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1127313/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1127313/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2019-05-17","Yemen: Military Intervention","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, with reference to the bombings at (a) a Sanaa school on 7 April 2019, (b) a Save the Children-supported hospital on 26 March 2019 and (c) other bombings of civilian infrastructure in Yemen, what discussions he has had with his Saudi counterpart on the timeframe for the conclusion of the Saudi-led Coalition’s investigations into those incidents; and whether the results of those investigations will be made publicly available.","false","Biography information for Richard Burden","Birmingham, Northfield","Richard Burden","255648"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1127314","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2019-05-28","<p>We have been clear that all parties to the conflict in Yemen must comply with international humanitarian law. We continue to call on all parties to exercise restraint and implement the Stockholm Agreement without delay in order to improve the humanitarian situation in Yemen</p>","South West Wiltshire","Dr Andrew Murrison",,"2019-05-28T10:51:15.123Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1127314/answer","Biography information for Dr Andrew Murrison","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1127314/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1127314/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2019-05-17","Yemen: Military Intervention","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, what diplomatic steps he is taking to help ensure that deconflicted (a) hospitals and (b) schools in Yemen are protected from bombing.","false","Biography information for Richard Burden","Birmingham, Northfield","Richard Burden","255649"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1127315","Department for Transport","false","2019-05-22","<p>The main civil engineering works contracts for Phase One of HS2 were awarded in July 2017 to 4 joint ventures comprising European and British construction firms. The Department has not assessed any proposal to award a wholesale package to build High Speed Two.</p><p> </p><p> </p>","Wealden","Ms Nusrat Ghani",,"2019-05-22T10:18:37.043Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1127315/answer","Biography information for Ms Nusrat Ghani","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1127315/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1127315/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2019-05-17","High Speed 2 Railway Line","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, whether his Department has made an assessment of the potential effect of proposals to award five state-run Chinese companies a wholesale package to build High Speed Two on the financial sustainability of UK (a) civil engineering contractors, (b) supplier chains and (c) steel-making companies.","false","Biography information for Tulip Siddiq","Hampstead and Kilburn","Tulip Siddiq","255691"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1127316","Department of Health and Social Care","false","2019-05-24","<p>The Department currently has no plans to make an estimate of the cost to the National Health Service of violent crime.</p><p>However, the report ‘The economic and social costs of crime’<em>,</em> published by the Home Office, includes information on the costs associated with physical and emotional harms as a consequence of crime for health services. The report is available at the following link:</p><p><a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/the-economic-and-social-costs-of-crime" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/the-economic-and-social-costs-of-crime</a></p>","Thurrock","Jackie Doyle-Price",,"2019-05-24T12:36:24.22Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1127316/answer","Biography information for Jackie Doyle-Price","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1127316/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1127316/answer",,,,,"17","Health and Social Care","Health and Social Care","2019-05-17","NHS: Crimes of Violence","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health and Social Care, pursuant to the Answer of 16 May 2019 to Question 252108 on Crimes of Violence, whether his Department has plans to make an estimate of the cost to the NHS of violent crime.","false","Biography information for Vicky Foxcroft","Lewisham, Deptford","Vicky Foxcroft","255688"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1127317","Department of Health and Social Care","false","2019-05-22","<p>Obesity and poor diet are risk factors for bowel cancer in young people.</p><p>The second chapter of the world-leading childhood obesity plan was published in June 2018. This builds on the real progress made since the publication of chapter one in 2016, particularly in reformulation of the products our children eat and drink most. In chapter two we have set a bold ambition to halve childhood obesity by 2030 and significantly reduce the gap in obesity between children from the most and least deprived areas by 2030.</p><p>Many of the measures in both chapters of the plan will have an impact on tackling obesity across all age groups. These include the soft drinks industry levy, sugar reduction and wider calorie reformulation programme, restricting promotions and calorie labelling in restaurants which will improve our eating habits and reduce the amount of sugar we consume.</p><p>‘Childhood obesity: a plan for action, chapter 2’ is available at the following link:</p><p><a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/childhood-obesity-a-plan-for-action-chapter-2" target="_blank">www.gov.uk/government/publications/childhood-obesity-a-plan-for-action-chapter-2</a></p>","South Ribble","Seema Kennedy",,"2019-05-22T14:24:08.32Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1127317/answer","Biography information for Seema Kennedy","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1127317/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1127317/answer",,,,,"17","Health and Social Care","Health and Social Care","2019-05-17","Bowel Cancer: Young People","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health and Social Care, what steps he is taking to reduce the number of young people developing bowel cancer.","false","Biography information for Mr Jim Cunningham","Coventry South","Mr Jim Cunningham","255652"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1127318","Department for Transport","false","2019-05-24","<p>In 2018 Office for Low Emission Vehicle Ministers wrote to Local Authority leaders encouraging them to support the uptake of electric vehicles and apply to the On-street Residential Chargepoint Scheme. This scheme provides grant funding to Local Authorities to install chargepoints at on-street locations for residents that lack off-street parking. Ministers also announced a further £4.5m for the scheme (£2m for 18/19 and £2.5m for 19/20). In addition, OLEV and the Energy Savings Trust have hosted a series of on-street charging workshops providing over 200 Local Authorities with more information on the scheme. The Office for Low Emission Vehicles have regular discussion with Local Authorities on recharging infrastructure.</p><p> </p><p>We have also provided £40m to eight Go Ultra Low Cities, around £20 million for dedicated taxi infrastructure and recently announced over £12.5 million for bus recharging infrastructure under the ultra low emission bus scheme.</p>","Northampton North","Michael Ellis",,"2019-05-24T13:19:29.09Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1127318/answer","Biography information for Michael Ellis","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1127318/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1127318/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2019-05-17","Electric Vehicles: Charging Points","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, what discussions his Department has had with local authorities on (a) improving the availability of electric car charging points and (b) funding for those charging points.","false","Biography information for Jim Fitzpatrick","Poplar and Limehouse","Jim Fitzpatrick","255647"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1127319","Department of Health and Social Care","false","2019-05-24","<p>This data is not available. The fact that a person who self harms or takes their own life is a family member of a victim of violence is not routinely recorded by the National Health Service.</p>","Thurrock","Jackie Doyle-Price",,"2019-05-24T12:58:26.447Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1127319/answer","Biography information for Jackie Doyle-Price","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1127319/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1127319/answer",,,,,"17","Health and Social Care","Health and Social Care","2019-05-17","Self-harm and Suicide ","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health and Social Care, pursuant to the Answer of 16 May 2019 to Question 252092 on Self-Harm and Suicide, where data on (a) self-harm and (b) suicide among family members of victims of violence is held.","false","Biography information for Vicky Foxcroft","Lewisham, Deptford","Vicky Foxcroft","255689"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1127320","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2019-05-29","<p>Our published draft Environment (Principles and Governance) clauses form part of our broader Environment Bill.</p><p> </p><p>The draft clauses set out the environmental principles and the creation of a policy statement together with a new system of green governance for when we leave the EU.</p><p> </p><p>Further measures being planned for the Environment Bill will help us take action to enhance our environment, including wildlife habitats.</p>","Suffolk Coastal","Dr Thérèse Coffey",,"2019-05-29T13:00:49.263Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1127320/answer","Biography information for Dr Thérèse  Coffey","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1127320/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1127320/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2019-05-17","Wildlife: Conservation","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, what assessment he has made of the efficacy of measures to protect wildlife habitats in the Draft Environment (Principles and Governance) Bill 2018; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Vernon Coaker","Gedling","Vernon Coaker","255654"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1127321","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2019-05-22","<p>Targets play an important role in driving action to reduce emissions from pollution sources to improve air quality. This is why we have committed to setting a new long term target for PM<sub>2.5 </sub>in our Clean Air Strategy, in addition to meeting our 2020 and 2030 emissions ceilings under the EU National Emission Ceilings Directive. We will publish evidence soon on what action would be needed to meet WHO guidelines.</p>","Suffolk Coastal","Dr Thérèse Coffey",,"2019-05-22T15:45:40.497Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1127321/answer","Biography information for Dr Thérèse  Coffey","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1127321/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1127321/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2019-05-17","Air Pollution","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, what assessment he has made of the efficacy of legally binding targets for reducing air pollutants; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Vernon Coaker","Gedling","Vernon Coaker","255655"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1127322","Home Office","false","2019-05-22","<p>We remain fully committed to fulfilling our commitments under section 67 of the Immigration Act 2016. Over 220 children were transferred to the UK under section 67 when the Calais camp was cleared in late 2016. Since then we have been making further progress with participating States to refer and transfer more eligible children to move closer to the commitment to transfer 480 children.</p><p>Relocation of eligible children to the UK is dependent on the availability of appropriate local authority care placements. The Home Office recognises the highly valuable work that local authorities undertake in supporting unaccompanied asylum-seeking children (UASC) which is why we have significantly increased the funding paid as a contribution to their costs. It is hoped that this will enable more local authorities to feel able to offer placements for vulnerable UASC, and we will be working with them and partners to encourage this.</p>","Romsey and Southampton North","Caroline Nokes",,"2019-05-22T13:01:36.327Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1127322/answer","Biography information for Caroline Nokes","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1127322/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1127322/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2019-05-17","Refugees: Children","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, what steps he is taking to ensure that unaccompanied child refugees will continue to be transferred under the Dubs scheme in the next twelve months.","false","Biography information for Mr Jim Cunningham","Coventry South","Mr Jim Cunningham","255653"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1127323","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2019-05-23","<p>The Environment Bill will be introduced early in the second Session of this Parliament.</p>","Suffolk Coastal","Dr Thérèse Coffey",,"2019-05-23T10:14:08.78Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1127323/answer","Biography information for Dr Thérèse  Coffey","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1127323/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1127323/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2019-05-17","Environment Protection","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, when he plans to introduce the Environment Bill; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Vernon Coaker","Gedling","Vernon Coaker","255656"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1127324","Department for Digital, Culture, Media and Sport","false","2019-05-23","<p>DCMS, in partnership with the National Lottery Community Fund, is providing over £2m to OnSide Youth Zones through the Youth Investment Fund (2017-2020). This is supporting the expansion and creation of open access youth services in the Wirral, Wolverhampton and Barking and Dagenham.</p><p> </p><p>Local programmes funded by DCMS and delivered through delivery partners are also delivered in OnSide Youth Zones. For example a money management programme through the Savers Support Fund, programmes through the Sport for Development fund and National Citizen Service local delivery.</p>","Eastleigh","Mims Davies",,"2019-05-23T14:48:21.17Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1127324/answer","Biography information for Mims Davies","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1127324/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1127324/answer",,,,,"10","Digital, Culture, Media and Sport","Digital, Culture, Media and Sport","2019-05-17","OnSide Youth Zones","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Digital, Culture, Media and Sport, with reference to the oral contribution of the Home Secretary of 15 May 2019, Official Report, column 274, how much Government funding was provided to OnSide Youth Zones from (a) 2015 to (b) 2018.","false","Biography information for Vicky Foxcroft","Lewisham, Deptford","Vicky Foxcroft","255690"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1127325","Department for Transport","false","2019-05-23","<p>The offence of trespass is subject to a fine up to £1000. DfT is not aware of any plans for this to be increased. In addition a Penalty Notice for Disorder can be issued to any offender over 18 years of age and the amount is currently £60.</p><p> </p><p>Prosecutions are a matter for the police and the courts. However, as well as prosecutions there are other measures available to the police including a caution, community resolution, or other outcomes outside of the justice system.</p><p> </p>","Harrogate and Knaresborough","Andrew Jones",,"2019-05-23T14:10:40.937Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1127325/answer","Biography information for Andrew Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1127325/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1127325/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2019-05-17","Railways: Trespass","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, what the fine is for trespassing on national rail lines; whether his Department plans to increase the penalties for such trespass; and what steps his Department is taking to ensure that such trespassers are prosecuted.","false","Biography information for Daniel Kawczynski","Shrewsbury and Atcham","Daniel Kawczynski","255666"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1127326","Department for Transport","false","2019-05-23","<p>In (a) 2017:- according to British Transport Police data there were 121 convictions for trespass and (b) in 2018 there were 139.</p>","Harrogate and Knaresborough","Andrew Jones",,"2019-05-23T13:58:45.327Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1127326/answer","Biography information for Andrew Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1127326/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1127326/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2019-05-17","Railways: Trespass","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, how many successful prosecutions there were of people trespassing on national rail lines in (a) 2017 and (b) 2018.","false","Biography information for Daniel Kawczynski","Shrewsbury and Atcham","Daniel Kawczynski","255667"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1127327","Department of Health and Social Care","false","2019-05-22","<p>No specific assessment has been made by the Department at this time.</p><p>Care for children with Diffuse Intrinsic Pontine Glioma (DIPG) is co-ordinated and provided by Children’s Cancer Principal Treatment Centres (PTCs) working in conjunction with Paediatric Oncology Shared Care Units. Children’s Cancer PTCs are responsible for planning and delivering treatment for children with DIPG as well as ensuring these children can access wider support services such as psychology services, specialist play services and other therapies.</p>","South Ribble","Seema Kennedy",,"2019-05-22T14:25:19.6Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1127327/answer","Biography information for Seema Kennedy","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1127327/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1127327/answer",,,,,"17","Health and Social Care","Health and Social Care","2019-05-17","Brain Cancer","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health and Social Care, what assessment he has made of access to NHS support for sufferers of diffuse intrinsic pontine glioma.","false","Biography information for Gill Furniss","Sheffield, Brightside and Hillsborough","Gill Furniss","255692"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1127328","Department for Education","false","2019-05-22","<p>Social mobility is one of my right hon. Friend, the Secretary of State for Education’s top priorities. We welcome the thorough analysis in the Social Mobility Commission’s State of the Nation 2018-19 report, and the important work that Dame Martina Milburn and her commissioners are doing to promote social mobility across the United Kingdom.</p><p>We are going through the recommendations in the report carefully, however in keeping with previous reports, we do not plan to publish a formal government response.</p>","Stratford-on-Avon","Nadhim Zahawi",,"2019-05-22T11:46:54.247Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1127328/answer","Biography information for Nadhim Zahawi","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1127328/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1127328/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2019-05-17","Social Mobility","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, when his Department plans to publish a response to the report published by the Social Mobility Commission entitled, State of the Nation 2018-19: Social Mobility in Great Britain Social Mobility in Great Britain.","false","Biography information for Angela Rayner","Ashton-under-Lyne","Angela Rayner","255682"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1127329","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2019-05-23","<p>The information provided is taken as at 30 April 2019.</p><p> </p><table><tbody><tr><td><p><strong>Year</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>Number of Secondments from EA</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>Of which are still working in the department* </strong></p></td></tr><tr><td><p><strong>a) June 2016 – All secondments from EA to Defra from June 2016 to April 2019.</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>74</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>12</strong></p></td></tr><tr><td><p><strong>b) Last 12 Months – Those whose secondments started between May 2018 and April 2019. These are included in the number above.</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>7</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>Less than 5</strong></p></td></tr><tr><td><p><strong>c) April 2019 – Those whose secondments started in April 2019. These are included in both figures above.</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>0</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>0</strong></p></td></tr></tbody></table><p> </p><p>*These are the number of staff whose secondments have not yet come to an end, and are therefore still working in Defra. Those whose secondments have come to an end will have returned to the Environment Agency.</p><p> </p><p>Secondments usually last for two years, however we would expect there to be some variation in length dependant on business needs.</p><p> </p><p>We have chosen to withhold the information relating to the number of staff still in the department whose secondments started in the last 12 months in line with GDPR regulations, as it relates to less than 5 members of staff and therefore there is a risk they may be identified.</p>","Macclesfield","David Rutley",,"2019-05-23T13:16:32.803Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1127329/answer","Biography information for David Rutley","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1127329/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1127329/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, 